segments.text: We're in the office of Bruce McClendon in the municipal building of Fort Worth.
Bruce, after you left Galveston, you went to Beaumont, and tell us a little bit about the program in Beaumont and what your role in that was.
Well, Beaumont was just as much of a challenge as Galveston in that
It was the right time.
Something needed to be done and people wanted it done.
The manager who hired me, Ray Riley, was outstanding.
He and his classmates from that particular class of KU all turned out to be very successful.
It's Anderson in Dallas, Lou Fox in
San Antonio, Muhlenbeck, who was down in Galveston, and Ray Riley.
And I thought Ray Riley was the one who was more skilled, more gifted as a manager than any of the others.
He is now working in the private sector and the head of a major corporation down here in the Beaumont area, a very successful individual.
But Ray had a little bit of a planning background.
He had interned up in the Kansas City, Lawrence area in a planning kind of capacity.
So he knew the terminology, he knew the techniques, he knew the deficiencies that existed, and he gave me
broad marching orders to basically create a planning program to do something with respect to planning.
Everything they had was 20 or 30 years old.
They had old comprehensive plans, old zoning, old subdivision regulations, no capital improvements programming.
A planner's dream.
I mean, here you're given the resources and the direction to do something.
Who had been the planning director previously?
Somebody from Chicago had been brought in
for a couple of years.
Anderson, I believe, was his name, John Anderson.
And John was a regional, had come from a regional planning commission.
And there was a big jump from regional planning to municipal planning.
I don't think John and I have been able to make that jump.
And he had a young staff out of the way, part of the state.
So he really didn't have the staff in place or the experience, in my judgment, to be as effective as he put it in.
And he tended to sit on his staff a little bit.
I was a little bit afraid of them for the younger ones that did have some energy initiative.
Well, our first priority was to do the zoning ordinance.
And it took about a year, year and a half, very controversial.
They had a 25-year-old zoning ordinance, Beaumont, that historically did anti-regulation.
They had passed zoning in something like 1948.
And then the year after that, the public referendum, they rejected zoning.
And then back in about 1954, 55,

the zoning wave came again and basically the development community produced an ordinance that, you know, was kind of one of those things where if we're going to have zoning, it might be something we can live with.
So we had this ordinance.
It was only about 40 pages long.
Very skimpy, cumulative zoning.
It was more of a devious kind of ordinance.
The district labels, for example, didn't link up to what the district really was, so you could come in and get R3 zoning, residential multifamily zoning, and they ended up allowing commercial, too.
It was all sorts of... Well, then you revised the zoning ordinance, and then after that, what was the... Revised the zoning ordinance, very controversial, very emotional experience.
It took us a year and a half because the ordinance was so old.
Recall was threatened.
Lots of things happened there.
But when the smoke finally cleared on that, we got a new ordinance in place that's a very good format, good model for the format that can be used by other places.
To implement, as part of the implementation process, we incorporated some aspects of our plan into our zoning ordinance, which makes that a little bit unique in that sense.
And we used that as a springboard then to develop our comprehensive plan.
They had been trying to do a comprehensive plan for about five years, but there was a lot of data in place.
It meant in a very short period of time, less than a year, we were able to reduce the land use.
Really, the first element was the park and open space element, followed shortly thereafter by the land use element of the comprehensive plan.
We did the park and open space because, A, we needed something less controversial at the zoning ordinance.
We had to try to earn our spurs and win our way back into the community.
So we did the park and open space plan, did establish the process and the format, issue-oriented planning process with measurable objectives as a result of the final product.
We had a plan that we called, that we described as the goals, objectives, policies, and proposals.
We presented this in the graphic format.
We tried to use the unified submarine approach of Kent.
We produced, our plan that was actually published was a fold-out brochure
that fit into the pocket of the plan itself.
The next step was to do the land use plan.
The land use plan was completed while I was there.
We were able to go through one and I think two update cycles of the park and open space plan where we, in essence,
evaluated our accomplishments during the past year, identified new issues that emerged, proposed solutions or treatments to those issues, and set a work program for the following year.
We called it an action plan, which was really a one-year detailed program for implementation of our plan.
We were able to start the cycle on the land use element.
When the plans were adopted, they contained language that required that they be reviewed and updated annually, and report from the staff and commission actioned by the city council.
Did it bother you at all that the zoning ordinance rewrite preceded the development of the comprehensive plan?
Sure.
In theory, you know, we all, everybody knows the theory that we should be planning before we do zoning.
And the one reason it took us a year and a half to do the zoning was because we did some of the planning.
With your left hand while you were doing the zoning with your right, I suppose.
Well, and we integrated into the ordinance.
I mean, because people couldn't understand.
If we had been trying to do the planning on the side, we wouldn't have gone very far.
So we took elements of the plan, the principles, concepts, and standards for residential, commercial, and industrial development.
These were actually integrated into the text of the plan itself.
So there was an understanding of the planning foundation of the ordinance that we were going through.
This was the only thing I could do because
The priority was to do the update to zoning ordinance.
The council wanted it, the manager wanted it, so we had to pursue it.

What's really ironic about that is when the development community tried to stop the updating process, and that's one reason why I drug out for a year and a half, but as their last gas effort to stop it,

they started lecturing the council that it was important that you do planning before you do zoning, and that we ought to defer the plan, the zoning, until we can complete updating the comprehensive plan.
That's ironic.
Yeah, it was really, really interesting.
And, of course, once we finished the plan, the ordinance, the development community said, well, what's all the rush on the plan now?
Uh-huh.
Sure.
But it was actually the Chamber of Commerce that was beating the drums at the very end for a comprehensive plan.
It's the way it ought to be.
Yes, it should have been.
Where were they when I got there?
So I was there three and a half, four years and the last thing that we did was the
capital improvements program.

The first time that city had a legitimate real world program, capital improvements program with priorities, analysis of the fiscal funding sources, identification of where the money was going to come from to fund the various capital projects.
And the plan itself was reviewed annually, I suppose, as a basis for the CIP.
The plan, in fact, that was the first block we checked was conformance with the plan and whether or not we were integrating or implementing the comprehensive plan.
Are there any cities that you're aware of in Texas that have this kind of relationship between zoning and CIP and the conference plans?
No, to my knowledge, the Beaumont system is just far superior.
We took the theory and we made it work there.
Terrific opportunity.
You know, again, the manager was there.
We had, Maury Myers was the mayor who was
He's probably the most outstanding mayor in the United States.
He and Henry Cisneros are peas in a pod in terms of their judgmental leadership ability.
He resigned, or when his term was up, he did not run again.
And he is now the mayor again because of all the trouble they're having.
In Beaumont, he came back.
and put himself back in the harness and ran for office again.
Because of the economy?
Because of the economy and the downturn.
He was just that kind of a person that he couldn't turn his back on his community.
When he didn't run again, it wasn't because the community didn't want him.
It was that he wanted to do other things, and he had given his public service.
Just looking back over your career here in Texas, beginning with Corpus Christi and then moving on to Galveston and then Beaumont and Fort Worth,

It sounds to me like you tried certain things out initially in Corpus Christi and were frustrated there because of management and the whole political climate, then moved on to Gauss and you were able to do a little bit more, and then when you got to Beaumont you found that the ground had already been fertilized, so that you were given more or less a free hand to exercise
theory and apply it to a practical situation.
That's a very good summary.
There is no question that in terms of effectiveness, my most effective program was BOVA.
On a scale of 1 to 10, it was a 9.
In Galveston,
Because I was there shorter and there was so much less that I could do, I would say my effectiveness was a seven.
But I was real pleased with the Galveston achievements, too.
We were able to, the bottom line was results.
We produced big results.
There was tremendous payback in Galveston.
But in Beaumont, I was able to put the theory to practice and something to come from it.
And the implementation resulted and took place.
So it was a planner's dream.
Now, you were in Beaumont at the time that you were elected to the presidency of APA.
That's right.
What were the circumstances that prompted you to run for national office?
Well, I had been president of the Texas chapter of APA.
Who was the vice president then?
Who was the vice president then?
I couldn't tell you.
I don't know.
You'll find out.
It's funny.
Sarah Jane was the secretary and treasurer on that board.
I do not remember who the vice president was.
We'll fill it in later.
In my involvement is the chapter president.

I serve in the chapter president's council, which is a board of chapter presidents all across the country that meets at the national level and advise and serves in a little bit of an advisory capacity to the national APA board.
Well, in that capacity, we dealt with primarily the budget issue.
increasing the dues and the National Board was of the opinion we needed to increase our dues a substantial amount, 20, 25 percent.
I was of the opinion and other members of the chapter that if there was a big gap between the National Board and what the members and what the members
felt and wanted from their organization.
And I met those people on the National Board and they were respected, influential, higher up people in planning.
And my assessment of them was that they weren't close to the customer.
That they had been involved in the profession for so many years and had risen to such a level that they couldn't remember their roots.
their experiences as planter ones and planter twos, and they didn't have contact with these entry-level or mid-range type planters.
So they didn't know what the heart of the profession was all about anymore.
And I thought they were insensitive and uncaring in a sense, and very egotistical.
It was almost the all AICP kind of thing.
I really did perceive that they didn't really care.
And we thought and we did a lot of work as the chapter presidents
to advise the APA board.
And the response from the APA board was just to brush us off as if we didn't know anything, didn't have anything to contribute.

And their view was they knew as much about the organization and the needs of the members as we did, and that they were in touch with the membership and it was us, the chapter presidents, that were out of touch.
And the national board, as I remember at that time, had historically been composed of people from
The Eastern Seaboard community.
From the Eastern Seaboard, and they were predominantly academicians with a sprinkling of practicing consultants.
Probably on a 21-member board, I think only two or three may have been city planner types, you know, senior planners, or they were most of, you know, a planning director kind of person.
Sure.
They were not what the heart of the organization was.
Because we can't put down academicians.
No, only in the sense of the domination.
I don't think.
I saw something that says that the academic community constitutes 8% or 9% of the APA membership.
If you're representing 8% of the membership and you have 60% of the board, there's an imbalance there.
And there was an imbalance.
So I came home and I was madder than hell from the meeting.
And the more I started paying attention to what APA was doing,
and the little newsletters that they would send out in their news and whatever it is.
It became clearer and clearer to me that there wasn't grassroots inaction there, that the board had lost touch with the membership.
other chapter presidents shared this frustration with me.
And they called me and said, and I had been, as you know me, I had been pretty visible in my capacity on the chapter presidents council.
I'm very opinionated and I'm a strong fighter and a promoter.
And so I've promoted our position very strongly and impressed some people.
They felt like here's a person who cares and here's a person who can carry our banner.
So there were folks that called me and said,
we need to do something about billing candidates, running for the board, trying to make our position known, and have a referendum on what it is we're all about.
So I said, well, let me see if we can find somebody.
So I tried to call, I tried to get Mary Lou Henry, who was the person I knew most about, who just, I'd followed her as chapter president or at this point here.
Really, she'd been out of office for one term before I followed her.
And Mary Lou,
was a knowledgeable, informed, educated, just outstanding individual.
So I tried to get Mary Lou to run for the board and for the president.
I said, that's how you're going to make a statement.
One position out of 21 can't do anything unless it's the president.
So I tried to talk Mary Lou into running.
She was appreciative of the offer, but couldn't do it because a good friend of hers from California
Okay, at Pomona.
Cal State at Pomona.
Margarita McCoy.
Margarita McCoy had already been nominated and she couldn't run against Margarita.
Well, we could run against Margarita.
What it came down to is when I reported back to this little network that had been creating attractive presidents, a decision was made that I would run.
I think everybody that really knows me has always understood that it wasn't me running because I wanted to run at that time.
I really had other things to do.
I had a new job, and it was up to my neck.
And we couldn't recruit a viable candidate.
And I had a lot of fire in the stomach, in the belly, as the expression goes.
So I took on the challenge.
I really didn't campaign that hard.
I used the network that I had built up over the years.
I ran through the nomination process.
I had chapter presidents circulating my petition.
I had over 200 people from across the country that signed.
You were a write-in candidate.
Yes, I was a write-in candidate.
Nobody had ever been successful as a write-in candidate before.
Nobody wanted to try it again.
And no one from Texas had been president before.
No one from Texas had been president.
We had one person that had served on the board.
In fact, no one from the southwest part of the country had ever been president of APA.
Sure, he had also been on the board.
Of the old AIP.
Yeah.
Or ASPO.
He'd been on the board of the old ASPO.
And no city planner.
had ever been president of APA.
They had always been academicians.
They had always been consultants.
I was the first
City planner.
Practicing city planner to be on APA presidents.
That's remarkable.
Yeah.
Or as polar AIP, according to the staff there in Washington.
And they were able to do the research on things.
We had people who had been practicing at some point in their career that had become presidents, but no sitting, no practicing person had done it.
In terms of accomplishments you indicated before, there's a couple of them.
The long term, the short term ones,
were that I was able to take some very emotional, confrontational issues involving things like where's the office going to be located, what was going to happen to our magazine.
There's some things I was able to do.
And the position of the executive director.
weren't able to do anything about the position of the executive director.
That was very controversial.
That was controversial, and the executive director survived.
The board voted.
The year I took office, the board voted.
to retain his installment as executive director by one vote.
With, ironically, again enough, the student representative on the board casting the deciding vote.
Really?
So I often tell students... Who was that, McNutt?
No, it was a fellow from Yemigai, from back east, Cincinnati or someplace.
But for students who often say, why should I get involved in APA, how can I make a difference, or whatever it was, one student cast one vote that made a difference as to our executive director.
In my election, there were also some other malcontents that were elected, some people that didn't like the system.
This was the first emergence, really, of the Dan Lauber faction into outreach capacity.
There was a Lauber faction consisting of people like Bill Toner and Edie Netter and himself, but they were former APA PASPOL staffers who used to work for the organization.
You'd come back in, you understood the system, knew how to manipulate it, knew how to win an election process and they were there.
Well this was the first year that Lauber reached out
How do you say that?
L-A-U-B-E-R. L-A-U-B-E-R. And his first name is?
Daniel.
Dan.
And there was a faction on the board.
There was this more of the old-timer, elitist group.
They'd be classified or described as the AICP faction.
And then there was this Lauber faction that was started out in the guise of, he called it the good old planter, which was the average planter out there.
And Lauber thought,
that the board was missing.
He thought like I did in that sense, that the board wasn't responsive.
Now as time evolved and as my term went on, I learned after about a year that Dan Lauber basically had his own views of the organization and that

his views really were not grassroots, that he really didn't have a desire to listen to the customer, so to speak, and be responsive to the membership, as much as he had his own ideas of what the membership wanted, and he felt like it ought to be run in that fashion.
So in a sense, in my experience on the board, was he started replacing the elitism of AICP with the elitism of Dan Lauber.
And I came in as the grassroots.
Bill from the bottom up.
And I think one of my contributions is the involvement is that I became a focal point.
I needed credibility to this perspective.
And chapter presidents like Jim Duncan linked up with him.
From Florida.
From Florida.
Yeah, from Florida.
linked up and saw, and I gave them a focal point for them to become involved in, and I pointed them to positions on the board, both Jim and Norman Staniford, who's also from Florida.
People who were the grassroots kind of organization, very non-assuming,
Unegotistical.
Folks who cared about the organization, who cared about making the organization more responsive to the members.
Folks who believed in the Toffler and the, who wrote the Megatrends.
That's the deal about building from the grassroots into what's the problem with these large organizations.
And we put something in place, we put our system in place, which was basically using the mechanism of the chapter presidents
to battle Lauber's system in place, which was his Inside AGA newsletter and the network that had been built up in that newsletter over the years.

Again, Lauber's newsletter was intended to manipulate and get backing behind him for his positions, as opposed to the chapter presidents, who really went out with the grassroots, open mind, let us be responsive to what you can do.
Where is Lauber?
Where does he come from?
Lauber's in Chicago, and he's got his own
quasi-consulting firm.
He just, you know, he probably reports $15,000 a year income or something.
A very modest living fellow who was working on the law degree when he was on the board.
In fact, got his, passed his bar exam the year he was president.
My last year, my first year on the board, I was completely ineffective.
The only thing I accomplished in that first year was moving the APA conference from the national conference from Houston to San Antonio.
My second year as president, I was relatively effective because there were some outsiders that were brought in on the board.
The first year I was elected, there were more that were brought in the second year.
And I started to earn some respect on my positions.
And basically, it's like anything you go into.
I was an outsider.
I was not trusted.
I was put down in my first year.
Second year, people respected the heck out of me.
I did some very positive things.
We built, we pulled, as opposed to destroying.
First year, I came in relatively negative.
Second year, I was able to build some things as a president and appoint some committees to make things happen.
And we were able to resolve some very controversial emotional issues that had dogged the organization for many years.
And so in a sense, I wasted a lot of my year in office
Solving the agenda, the problems that had existed for a number of years, I really wasn't able to do as much as I wanted to do and go into the areas that I wanted to do.
But I was effective for the organization.
And, uh, and the other board members told me at the end of my term that I had been more effective than they could remember in many, many, many years.
And they're very complimentary.
as to my term in office.
And it's self-supporting for me to say this.
And I hope as a follow-up on this, you might call the installment and ask him to assess my term in office.
When my term was up and I turned the gavel over to Dan Lauber to come in and take my place, there was enthusiastic applause from the board who was in place.
And Iz told me they couldn't remember that ever happening before.
And he said it was sincere, it was genuine, it was really a reflection of people's appreciation toward my term in office.
So I felt, as an egotist, I felt very pleased with that.
My third year on the board, as an immediate past president, was a complete wasted year.
Basically, it was a year where I tried to stop the things that Dan Lauber was doing.
Instead of being positive, I basically had to go into a, let's just, you know, reactive, and let's just try to stop this guy for one year.
I was trying to live through it.
So that was disappointing.
What was his basic point of view?
What was he trying to do with APA?
He was trying to kill AICP.
He was trying to dismantle the divisions.
He was trying to strangle, cut off the resources to the chapters.
Basically, he was trying to recreate an ASCO organization.
which is the organization he was exposed to as an employee.
He had worked for ASPO.
So he had worked for them, and he liked that kind of environment.
He tried to go back and recreate it.
I tend to come from the grassroots volunteer
perspective, and I wanted to see the organization build on the strength of our volunteers, not be centralized.
I was promoting decentralization, he was promoting centralization.
Well, that was the basic difference between ASPO and APA, or AIP in those days, was that AIP had a chapter structure, and it could rely on its membership throughout the country.
What I tried to do was take the strengths of both organizations
and build on them and get rid of the weaknesses and weed those things out, the things that we weren't doing well or that were detrimental.
There were many things ASPO did that are very solid, such as the technical publications.
No question, they had a superior
Their program was of more value to me growing up as a planner than AIP.

AIP did a better job of sharing the grassroots, the networking kind of thing, to check the functions, getting out where I was as an entry-level person where I couldn't go to some of the national things.
So what we really needed to do after the merger was do the best of both.
And there wasn't a faction.
that was opposed to anything of an old-ass pope, and there was a faction that was opposed to anything of the AIP.
The last year, my year's presidency, the factions really disintegrated and disappeared.
The AICP elitism was no longer there, but there was this emerging-ass pope thing that was very difficult to deal with, very emotional and confrontational.
One of the lasting contributions I made was this
these charter amendments where we provided for AICP to elect AICP to elect their own board.
We had a vicious cycle that was taking place where whoever ran with the strongest
position against AICP was getting elected to the AICP board.
We were literally bringing in people that were opposed to the organization.
So it became very important, if we're going to save it, to switch the balloting procedures so that AICP votes for AICP and the AICP commission.
The board is too complex to talk about now, but there's an APA board and an AICP commission.
I think that charter change
which Dan Louder fought like hell to stop, is what saved this organization.
If we didn't do that, I think even as early now as now, we would have a separatist movement.
We'd have a separate old AIP organization back again.
Or it could have possibly disintegrated into any number of regional professional organizations.
Well, in truth, that's what Jim Duncan and I were going to do.
As Florida chapter president, Jim, and I as Texas chapter president, we were going to create a Gulf Coast Planning Association with our membership at both ends providing the anchor.
And we had enough of a resource base.
And it would have killed APA.
Yeah, it would have.
But we weren't interested in killing APA.
We were really interested in trying to get their attention.
and build a stronger organization based on the grassroots permeation of our organization.
Well then, after Lauber left office, what... Well, now we have Norm Krumholz as president, and Norm doesn't have a mission.
Norm's not obsessed.
He basically has an academic orientation.
and he's just going to preside over the organization for a year.
Next year, Jim Duncan will assume a chapter of the national presidency.
And Jim has this chapter bias, this action orientation, the culture of the consumer business philosophy.
And you will see the organization become much more responsive next year.
As this labor element dissipates, the housekeeping of Krumholz will consume this year.
And then Jim will really have a stage set for him to get in there
And also the big change is that Jim will have a two-year term.
That was one of the other changes we made in our amendment process.
We revised our charter.
That makes a lot of sense.
Longer term in office.
One year, I was able to do some things.
A lot more than people thought I could in one year.
If I could have had another year as president, I could have had an even greater or more long-term lasting impact.
Oh yeah, I'm sure.
It takes about a year to get used to any different thing.
So that Jim Duncan will be the second Texan to be a national president.
That's correct.
He'll be the second practicing planner to make national president.
Well, let's move on then.
We've talked about Beaumont, and we've talked about your role with National APA and, of course, the Texas Chapter APA.
Now we are in Fort Worth.
How about if I hit Arlington for about five minutes?
Okay.
All right.
We don't want to forget Arlington.
Yeah, Arlington, I'd like to forget Arlington.
Everybody has an Arlington in their record somewhere, and I've got one, and that's Arlington.
In contrast to Beaumont, which was the height of my career in terms of effectiveness, Arlington was the absolute low point in my career in effectiveness.
I was not able to institute the programs and produce the products and results that I wanted to do.
What were the reasons for that?
Well, I came into a community that was very smug, a sense of arrogance, of superiority, that they were God's gift to the world.
You know, Arlington had grown tremendously in population in the past 10 or 20 years, from a population of 20,000 to 200 and almost 50,000.
Rapid growth.
They made the classic management mistake of...
assuming that luck was good management.
They assumed, because everything was relatively okay, that what they'd been doing was profitable.
In fact, it was the Houston Syndrome.
They were in an ideal location between Dallas and Fort Worth.
They were gaining all the benefits of everybody around them.
through no fault of their own or no actions of their own, their location.
It was a traditional real estate story about one of the three most important factors in real estate investment, location, location, location.
Hey, Arlington had the location.
They had a strong mayor who early in his career
He used a Chamber of Commerce approach.
He brought in General Motors and Washington Senators, became a Texas Rangers.
What was his name?
Vandergrift.
Outstanding individual.
He had the Chevrolet Buick.
Chevrolet dealer, yeah.
Well, wasn't he also big in Texas Municipal League?
I doubt it.
If he was, it would surprise me, but he might have been.
He had more of a Chamber of Commerce approach, not really in the government.
So I'd be surprised if he was involved in a government organization, but he could have been.
But...
had a planning commission that was dominated by a real estate interest.
I said, well, good grief, who's on here that represents the citizens?
And there was one woman on there, housewife, and she was working for the Chamber of Commerce.
And I said, well, how about the guy from the university?
I said, geez, at least there's an academic influence on here.
And it turns out that he was from the School of Business at UTA, which has a completely different philosophy than a liberal arts kind of professor or somebody.
So you had a commission that was hostile.
We had a city manager that says, it's time for us to do planning.
We haven't done it for 25 years.
We're paying for it.
Arlington has an extraordinary amount of bonded indebtedness, far more than any other city.
60% of the budget is used to retire bond and debt, you know, and the rule of thumb is 25%.
But it happened because they bought that growth.
Here this growth was coming anyway, but they subsidized the development community.
They did a fiscal impact study in the late 70s that showed that the population of the city had grown, the population had grown 50% during this study period.
Bonded indebtedness had gone up something like 900%, and per capita debt had gone up 400%.
So nobody could say that the debt was occurring because of the growth.
The debt was occurring because they subsidized too much of it.
They just underwrote the growth at public expense.
When this study was done, by the way, they boxed it up and shoved it in the closet.
It was never released to the public.
The public didn't know the significance of those fiscal implications.
But Vandegrift did, and his last act as he left when that study was there, they changed some of the participation policies, and the city was paying less from 77 or 78 on.
They paid less when Vandegrift left.
From that point on,
The developers had to pay a higher proportion of their costs.
The manager knew changes had to occur.
The council, which was politically responsive to the community, understood there was a growing groundswell of interest in preserving the quality of life.
The people were afraid they were losing what had brought them to Arlington to start with.
So, they went out, they recruited very heavily to bring in a really innovative, aggressive, you know, doer-oriented, results-oriented planer.
And I competed with some real good people, including somebody that's up here in the Metroplex, Matt Plano.
I'm not sure if you remember his name now.
It's not my name today.
He's the planer director in Plano.
Planer director in Plano.
But he's the North Central Texas chapter president.
